# Use inject() over constructor injection

In Angular components, directives, and `@Injectable` services, use the **`inject()`** function instead of constructor parameter injection (Angular 14+).

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — constructor injection
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class MyService {
  constructor(private readonly dep: OtherService) {}
}

// ✅ GOOD — inject()
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class MyService {
  private readonly dep = inject(OtherService);
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — constructor injection in a component
@Component({ ... })
export class MyComponent {
  constructor(private sanitizer: DomSanitizer) {}
}

// ✅ GOOD
@Component({ ... })
export class MyComponent {
  private readonly sanitizer = inject(DomSanitizer);
}
```

## When constructor injection is still appropriate

Plain TypeScript classes that are **not** Angular-managed (no `@Injectable`, `@Component`, `@Directive` decorator) and receive dependencies manually do not use Angular DI at all — constructor injection there is correct and should stay:

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT — plain class, not Angular DI
export class PenToolSession {
  constructor(private readonly ports: PenToolSessionPorts) {}
}
```

## Tokens and injection flags

`inject()` also accepts `InjectionToken`s and supports optional/self/skip-self flags:

```typescript
private readonly port = inject(MY_PORT_TOKEN);
private readonly optional = inject(SomeService, { optional: true });
```
